SIMPLE: flag
RECORDS: 8

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Flag
<hw>Flag</hw> <pr>(fl⟦acr⟧g)</pr>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. &
p. p.</pos> <conjf>Flagged</conjf> <pr>(fl⟦acr⟧gd)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. &
vb. n.</pos> <conjf>Flagging</conjf>
<pr>(fl⟦acr⟧g"g⟦icr⟧ng)</pr>.]</vmorph> <ety>[Cf. Icel. <ets>flaka</ets>
to droop, hang loosely. Cf. <er>Flacker</er>, <er>Flag</er> an
ensign.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To hang loose without stiffness; to bend
down, as flexible bodies; to be loose, yielding, limp.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>As loose it [the sail] <qex>flagged</qex> around the mast.</q>
<rj><qau>T. Moore.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To droop; to grow spiritless; to lose vigor; to
languish; <as>as, the spirits <ex>flag</ex>; the strength
<ex>flags</ex>.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The pleasures of the town begin to <qex>flag</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Swift.</qau></rj></p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- To droop; decline; fail; languish;
pine.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Flag</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Flag
<hw>Flag</hw> <pr>(fl⟦acr⟧g)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To
let droop; to suffer to fall, or let fall, into feebleness; <as>as, to
<ex>flag</ex> the wings</as>.</def> <rj><au>prior.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To enervate; to exhaust the vigor or elasticity
of.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Nothing so <qex>flags</qex> the spirits.</q>
<rj><qau>Echard.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Flag</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Flag
<hw>Flag</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Cf. LG. & G. <ets>flagge</ets>, Sw.
<ets>flagg</ets>, Dan. <ets>flag</ets>, D. <ets>vlag</ets>. See
<er>Flag</er> to hang loose.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>That which flags or
hangs down loosely.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A cloth usually bearing a device or devices and used
to indicate nationality, party, etc., or to give or ask information; --
commonly attached to a staff to be waved by the wind; a standard; a
banner; an ensign; the colors; <as>as, the national <ex>flag</ex>; a
military or a naval <ex>flag</ex>.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <sd>(a)</sd> <def>A group of feathers
on the lower part of the legs of certain hawks, owls, etc.</def>
<sd>(b)</sd> <def>A group of elongated wing feathers in certain
hawks.</def> <sd>(c)</sd> <def>The bushy tail of a dog, as of a
setter.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>One of the wing feathers next the
body of a bird; -- called also <altname>flag
feather</altname>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Black flag</b></col>. <cd>See under <er>Black</er>.</cd>
-- <mcol><col><b>Flag captain</b></col>, <col><b>Flag
leutenant</b></col></mcol>, <cd>etc., special officers attached to the
flagship, as aids to the flag officer.</cd> -- <col><b>Flag
officer</b></col>, <cd>the commander of a fleet or squadron; an admiral,
or commodore.</cd> -- <col><b>Flag of truse</b></col>, <cd>a white flag
carried or displayed to an enemy, as an invitation to conference, or for
the purpose of making some communication not hostile.</cd> --
<col><b>Flag share</b></col>, <cd>the flag officer's share of prize
money.</cd> -- <col><b>Flag station</b></col> <fld>(Railroad)</fld>,
<cd>a station at which trains do not stop unless signaled to do so, by a
flag hung out or waved.</cd> -- <col><b>National flag</b></col>, <cd>a
flag of a particular country, on which some national emblem or device,
is emblazoned.</cd> -- <col><b>Red flag</b></col>, <cd>a flag of a red
color, displayed as a signal of danger or token of defiance; the emblem
of anarchists.</cd> -- <col><b>To dip, the flag</b></col>, <cd>to mlower
it and quickly restore it to its place; -- done as a mark of
respect.</cd> -- <col><b>To hang out the white flag</b></col>, <cd>to
ask truce or quarter, or, in some cases, to manifest a friendly design
by exhibiting a white flag.</cd> -- <mcol><col><b>To hang the flag
half-mast high</b></col> <it>or</it> <col><b>To hang the flag
half-staff</b></col> <it>or</it> <col><b>To hang the flag at
half-staff</b></col></mcol>, <cd>to raise it only half way to the mast
or staff, as a token or sign of mourning.</cd> -- <mcol><col><b>To
strike the flag</b></col> <it>or</it> <col><b>To lower the
flag</b></col></mcol>, <cd>to haul it down, in token of respect,
submission, or, in an engagement, of surrender.</cd> -- <col><b>Yellow
flag</b></col>, <cd>the quarantine flag of all nations; also carried at
a vessel's fore, to denote that an infectious disease is on
board.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Flag</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 4 ====
HEADWORD: Flag
<hw>Flag</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <ety>[From <er>Flag</er> an
ensign.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To signal to with a flag or by waving
the hand; <as>as, to <ex>flag</ex> a train</as>; also used with
<ptcl>down</ptcl>; <as>as, to <ex>flag down</ex> a cab</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To convey, as a message, by means of flag signals;
<as>as, to <ex>flag</ex> an order to troops or vessels at a
distance</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To decoy (game) by waving a flag, handkerchief, or
the like to arouse the animal's curiosity.</def></p>

<p><q>The antelope are getting continually shyer and more difficult to
<qex>flag</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>T. Roosevelt.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Flag</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 5 ====
HEADWORD: Flag
<hw>Flag</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[From <er>Flag</er> to hang loose, to
bend down.]</ety> <fld>(Bot.)</fld> <def>An aquatic plant, with long,
ensiform leaves, belonging to either of the genera <gen>Iris</gen> and
<gen>Acorus</gen>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Cooper's flag</b></col>, <cd>the cat-tail (<spn>Typha
latifolia</spn>), the long leaves of which are placed between the staves
of barrels to make the latter water-tight.</cd> -- <col><b>Corn
flag</b></col>. <cd>See under 2d <er>Corn</er>.</cd> -- <col><b>Flag
broom</b></col>, <cd>a coarse of broom, originally made of flags or
rushes.</cd> -- <col><b>Flag root</b></col>, <cd>the root of the sweet
flag.</cd> -- <col><b>Sweet flag</b></col>. <cd>See <er>Calamus</er>,
<pos>n.</pos>, 2.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Flag</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 6 ====
HEADWORD: Flag
<hw>Flag</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <def>To furnish or deck out with
flags.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Flag</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 7 ====
HEADWORD: Flag
<hw>Flag</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Icel. <ets>flaga</ets>, cf. Icel.
<ets>flag</ets> spot where a turf has been cut out, and E.
<ets>flake</ets> layer, scale. Cf. <er>Floe</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn>
<def>A flat stone used for paving.</def> <rj><au>Woodward.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Geol.)</fld> <def>Any hard, evenly stratified
sandstone, which splits into layers suitable for flagstones.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Flag</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 8 ====
HEADWORD: Flag
<hw>Flag</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <def>To lay with flags of flat
stones.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The sides and floor are all <qex>flagged</qex> with . . .
marble.</q> <rj><qau>Sandys.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Flagellant</ent>⟦br⟧
